      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Pick ELT, pay even less -->
  <section class="py-16">
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="rounded-2xl border border-violet-500/30 bg-gradient-to-br from-violet-500/5 to-cyan-500/5 backdrop-blur p-8 md:p-12">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Pick ELT, pay even less</h2>
        <p class="text-slate-300 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
          Our meter reads what hits our disk. In <strong class="text-white">ETL mode</strong> (the dlt path), your data is normalized on our side — a 1 GB JSON export becomes ~3 GB of flat tables. The meter counts 3 GB.
        </p>
        <p class="text-slate-300 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
          In <strong class="text-white">ELT mode</strong> (the dbt path with our new IR layer), your data is streamed as compressed parquet directly to your warehouse's raw schema and normalized there with SQL. A 1 GB JSON export becomes ~0.8 GB of parquet on the wire. The meter counts 0.8 GB.
        </p>
        <p class="text-slate-300 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
          Same source. Same data. <strong class="text-violet-300">3.75× lower bill.</strong>
        </p>

        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mt-8">
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-800 bg-slate-950/60 p-5">
            <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-widest text-slate-500 mb-2">ETL mode</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">
              1 GB HubSpot JSON → ~3 GB of normalized tables.<br />
              Over Pro's 100 GB quota: <span class="text-white font-mono">$1.50</span> overage per run.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-violet-500/50 bg-slate-950/60 p-5">
            <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-widest text-violet-400 mb-2">ELT mode</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">
              1 GB HubSpot JSON → ~0.8 GB of parquet on the wire.<br />
              Over Pro's 100 GB quota: <span class="text-white font-mono">$0.40</span> overage per run.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="text-xs text-slate-500 mt-6 leading-relaxed">
          The mode selector lives on every pipeline — it's the first switch in the UI when you create a new one. Existing pipelines can flip modes with a migrate button. See <a href="/blog/real-cost-modern-data-stack" class="text-violet-400 underline hover:text-violet-300">the dedicated post</a> on when to pick which mode.
